metadata.name: Vermes #17
metadata.description:
vermes = worms (lat.)

Throughout world mythology and related literature, worms have been significant figures. Although they were once referred to as various creatures, including snakes, lindworms, serpents, and dragons, today the term "worm" carries both connotations of death and rebirth.

metadata.name: Glossolalia #32
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: Cosmic reaction #86
metadata.description:
As per my daily programming routine, this time I went to combine different circle algorithms, like my last work. This work, by using the optimized algorithm of packing and fields and combining them with a pattern for the inner connection of the circles, presents an artwork with high details that can be seen in large dimensions by plotting it. There are different variations, some of which are more detailed. The colors of some circles, at much higher resolutions, may look very slightly different.
_________________________

To see the artwork in high quality, open it in live view and add “&res=1 to 25” to the URL, This artwork can also be plotted in large dimensions.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: 3OHA #22
metadata.description:
This work is a representation of complex systems found in both nature and society. The artwork consists of simple recursively divided cells, showcasing the self-similarity that exists in many structures. The texture of each cell resembles the weave of fabric, emphasizing the interconnected nature of these systems. The patterns and structures generated by the artwork follow simple rules, yet the resulting composition is intricate and complex. This artwork highlights the way that simple elements can combine to form more complex systems, and prompts reflection on the underlying structures that shape our world. The texture which resembles fabric or weaved material is not an afterthought but was more the initial purpose of this work.

HALF OF THE MONEY WILL BE DONATED FOR THE EARTHQUAKE RELIEF FUND.

metadata.name: NYC-80 #11
metadata.description:
Even if this work was intended as an abstract study, the crowded, rhythmically repeating structures are reminiscent of the monumental, anonymous appearance of some large cities.
The appearance is determined by naive strong strokes and simple forms that give the picture a strong and self-confident expressiveness reminiscent of the art of the New York art scene of the 80s. The surfaces are deliberately not layered, in order to underline the impenetrability, but also to preserve the abstract painterly element.

metadata.name: A Simple Test #39
metadata.description:
===== A Simple Test =====

This project started as a harmless way to test mint outputs with varying aspect ratios in preparation for an upcoming project that I've spend several months on which will be called A Simple Fail and will be released on my main fxhash account: https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/bfos.art

<Read more about A Simple Fail @ https://www.bfos.art/projects/a-simple-fail>

I quickly realized how much I would love to collect these mints. So why not set this up as a derivative project at a friendly discount on my alt account?  While I have made tweaks from the base code for this project, I have not spent the extremely detailed amount of time as I have on A Simple Fail.  There will be outputs that will have muted color compositions.  Many will love these minimal outputs.  But, if you hate one of these special mints, just let me know and I'll be happy to purchase the token back from you within reason and for a limited time.

I'm not publishing this project with an intention of burning down from the initial mint number.  This isn't a project to get rich on.  I only hope that it is one that you and the community will find great delight in collecting!  

Please have fun with A Simple Test!

I will publish this project as disabled so I can test a few outputs.  If all goes well, I'll schedule the project for opening on a later date.


===== Interactions =====

{S}ave at current resolution
{G}rain switch

{1-6} Save at x multiple of screen size

metadata.name: Data Overload #25
metadata.description:
This is my first project that uses shaders (so no svg export). I'm revisiting a theme that I have touched in the past: the distant cityscape against a sky representing today's urban life. The overload of information to which we are all exposed invests us like electromagnetic waves coming from a rising star causing something close to a deadly wind. The collectors can experience with form factors and palette to create the piece that best pleases their taste. Only the mode of the piece will be randomly defined with the rarest gold one, as always.
- hit s to export a '.png' file

metadata.name: Magic Blocks #33
metadata.description:
Different patterns are combined in multiple groups based on harmony in the main blocks.
A random coordinate system is used to place these colored blocks.
Each block uses a quadruple color palette, with one color for the background and two colors randomly selected from the three main colors.
A shadow is a block of black and white that exists in different patterns.
In three different modes, these blocks can be viewed:
-Colorless and textureless blocks
-Textured blocks without backgrounds
-Backgrounds and textures for blocks
The shadow blocks can be made up of just one specific pattern, with different dimensions, or they can be made up of several patterns, all with different dimensions.
press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: Calligraphy #101
metadata.description:
Calligraphy is about formulating letters, not language. 

One of my first exercises as a design student (c. 1967) was learning to letter. Using a nib holding pen and India ink we sat for 5 weeks in class like monks constructing letters in the style of a font called 15th Century Chancery Italic Script. Our final grade was based on how well we hand lettered a paragraph. It was a grueling process that's why I remember it; quite the way to develop an appreciation for the letterforms and type faces. 

This algorithmic artwork is modern cuneiform. It is based on a theory I've developed called "Language of Vision" which in itself is an approach for creating a "plastic" image. The space-frame or background square consists of a subtle paper texture and defines the tablet. A resizable tile (spatial force) forms the boundary for a "stroke." The stroke within the tile element is created by joining two bezier curves. 

An algorithm called "fractions of the whole" is a "form of spatial organization" which divides the picture frame into randomly sized intervals along each axes that form the variable sized tile areas. The stroke is programmed to fit each area. This theory lends itself very nicely to algorithmic art and provides a general framework for generative art.

There is meaning in every image but that meaning comes from your experience and imagination.

Check out Dr. Bill Generative Art OG website @ drbillkolomyjec.com
